body:
In my `simulation_driver.cpp` file I am simulating my input i.e. clock `i_clk` using this for loop: 

```
	for(tc = 0; tc < (1 << 22); tc++){

		tb->i_clk = 0;
		tb->eval();
		
		tf->dump(tc);
		
		tb->i_clk = 1;
		tb->eval();
		
		tc = tc + 2;
		tf->dump(tc);

	}
```

For loop in the first paragraph sets `i_clk() = 0` and because of a change I immediately evaluate the model as well. 

In the second paragraph I use `tf->dump(tc)`. This is poorly documented inside `/usr/share/verilator/include/verilated_vcd_c.h` where there is only one comment saying:

```
   /// Write one cycle of dump data
```

So I assume it should write `tc` cycle (only one cycle) of data in the `tf`.

Then the third paragraph sets `i_clk() = 1` and because of a change I immediately evaluate the model as well. 

Fourth paragraph then increments `tc` by `2` and again uses `tf->dump(tc)` that I assume will write twice as more cycles of data to the file `tf` than it did before. 

But it looks like my interpretation of `tf->dump()`is COMPLETELY wrong, because the state when `i_clk = 0` is twice as long as `i_clk = 1` and I expected it to be vice versa. Please take a look at the image.

![Screenshot_2021-05-05_21-38-38](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/8915807/117199286-4ebe9f00-adea-11eb-8e61-453fc559899c.png)

Why is my result quite the oposite of what I expected? What is the correct interpretation of `tf->dump()`?
